              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6718589368739088666">When I was reading Anne Rice&apos;s &quot;Servant of the Bones&quot; last year, I could not decide if I cared much for her style or the story. It was not until I finished the book that I began thinking about both the story and the writing style. It took another three months before I realized how thought provoking her book had been for me. And that to me is the sign of a true artist. Since then I have enjoyed a few of her books and just finished &quot;Interview with the Vampire&quot; (Which I always thought was called &quot;I</span>
  <span id="freeText6718589368739088666" style="display:none">When I was reading Anne Rice's "Servant of the Bones" last year, I could not decide if I cared much for her style or the story. It was not until I finished the book that I began thinking about both the story and the writing style. It took another three months before I realized how thought provoking her book had been for me. And that to me is the sign of a true artist. Since then I have enjoyed a few of her books and just finished "Interview with the Vampire" (Which I always thought was called "Interview with a Vampire".) I've learned to love her style and looking forward to reading many more of her books.</span>
