<div id="review_856902958" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/856902958" />
    <a title="Kathleen " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17830025-kathleen"><img alt="Kathleen " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1381551258p2/17830025.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/856902958?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kathleen " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kathleen " href="/user/show/17830025-kathleen">Kathleen </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17830025-kathleen?shelf=average-joes">average-joes</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer856902958" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4200326883601318456">Okay, so it is kind of obvious that Anne Rice wrote this book right after Memnoch the Devil. Especially during Part 3 of the book. <br/>So the book starts off with Part 1, where a professor who uses the name Jonathan is approached by a genii named Azriel who would like his story known and written down. A lot of the narration up to the actual storytelling is drenched with foreshadowing, which filled me with suspense. It was confusing and surprisingly engaging. (Though Jonathan keeps telling us how ama</span>
  <span id="freeText4200326883601318456" style="display:none">Okay, so it is kind of obvious that Anne Rice wrote this book right after Memnoch the Devil. Especially during Part 3 of the book. <br />So the book starts off with Part 1, where a professor who uses the name Jonathan is approached by a genii named Azriel who would like his story known and written down. A lot of the narration up to the actual storytelling is drenched with foreshadowing, which filled me with suspense. It was confusing and surprisingly engaging. (Though Jonathan keeps telling us how amazingly gorgeous Azriel is, which was kind of annoying). <br />Azriel begins his story with how he grew up, as a boy in a Jewish family taken from Jerusalem to Babylon. The way Rice approached the culture and religion of Babylonians was well-researched and creative. Azriel sees spirits and Marduk (a spirit or real Babylonian god, it is left to interpretation) is one of them. This attracts the attention the temple priests and they want to use him as a sacrifice in a ritual that establishes the Persian conqueror, Cyrus, as the new ruler of Babylonia. <br />It is an eerie, creepy ritual that will result in Azriel's death, but he does it so all the Jews can go back to Jerusalem, which Cyrus has promised. But an evil priest and old spiritual woman hijack poor Azriel after the ritual when he is about to die and use an ancient ritual to turn him into the Servant of the Bones. Honestly, this was my favorite part of the book. It was so creepy and a little scary. <br />The next section of the book, Part 2, is about Azriel's adventures with his favorite master. He kind of briefly talks about the most recent one, which was actually my favorite single scene in the entire book. But he mostly skips over the rest of the other masters. Azriel, as a spirit, has trouble remembering his past until the very end, so we hear Azriel talking about different parts of his past while reminding us that he could't remember individual parts at the time, which was unique.<br />If the entire book was this, just Azriel's adventures as a genii in the ancient world, I would have liked it at more. Which brings me to Part 3. <br />Rice's Memnoch the Devil ideals really show through in this part. If you like Memnoch the Devil, then fine, I get it. I don't dislike it, I just see that it’s directed towards a rather narrow audience and is rather opinionated about Rice's personal religious views. This book is kind of like that, but not as much. I never quite understood Azriel's relationship with God. He seemed to believe in God as an all-powerful being, but also worshiped Marduk. But the parts about Jewish history and culture, ancient and modern, were interesting.<br />So Azriel is suddenly awakened to witness the murder of Esther Belkin. The reason for his awakening without a Master was never fully explained. Rice said on her website that it was the scene of Esther’s death that woken him. I kind of don’t buy that, but whatever. So Azriel meets Gregory Belkin and his grandfather discussing Esther’s death and the Servant of the Bones (the casket containing Azirel’s bones has been gifted down to the grandfather). The grandfather hates Gregory and gives him the cursed casket. <br />Gregory Belkin is the leader of The Temple of the Mind of God, a weird, wide-spread Jewish cult. Apparently he is incredibly rich from his career as a televangelist. (Rice wrote that Dora, the woman in her last book, Memnoch, was a televangelist too). <br />Azriel confronts Gregory and seems to simultaneously despise and love him, which wasn’t confusing at all. He sees Rachel, Gregory’s wife, mourning for Esther. Gregory is apparently evil and unkind to his wife and hired the killers that murdered Esther. So Azriel helps Rachel, who is dying of a disease, leave to die alone with him in Miami. <br />They have sex and Gregory and his henchmen find them, but not before Rachel kills herself. Gregory reveals that he has a crazy plan to take over the world and kill everyone undesirable in the Third World and other places. This plan was only revealed until about 30 pages before the book ended, so it felt kind of abrupt. Part 4 is the epilogue, more or less.<br />The amount of thought Rice put into Azriel’s powers and origin story was very impressive. It was entertaining during the first half, but I kind of had to force myself to read the second. She should have stuck to feel and set-up of the first half, but it was still an incredibly cool twist about the origins of genies.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4200326883601318456" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

